# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: win-loss-record-pitching
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/1968-major-league-baseball-season] The **1968 major league baseball season** began on April 10, 1968.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/1968-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 29, with the St.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/1968-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals and Detroit Tigers as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/1968-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 65th World Series on October 2 and ended with Game 7 on October 10.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/1968-major-league-baseball-season] In the second iteration of this World Series matchup, the Tigers defeated the Cardinals, four games to three, capturing their third championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1945.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/1968-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the St.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/1968-major-league-baseball-season] The 39th All-Star Game was held on July 9 at the Houston Astrodome in Houston, Texas, home of the Houston Astros.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/1968-major-league-baseball-season] The Kansas City Athletics moved to Oakland, California as the Oakland Athletics, being the eighth team since 1953 to relocate, and the fourth of American League teams since them.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/1968-major-league-baseball-season] Kansas City would be without a major league team for the 1968 season.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/1968-major-league-baseball-season] Legal pressure from the city moved the originally planned 1971 American League expansion up to 1969, which saw the enfranchisement of the Kansas City Royals.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/1968-major-league-baseball-season] The 1968 schedule consisted of 162 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had 10 teams.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/1968-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 18 games against the other nine teams of their respective league.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/1968-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place by the American League since the 1961 season and by the National League since the 1962 season.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/1968-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the last season with this format, as the following season would see a new format due to expansion and the creation of divisions.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/1968-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 10, featuring all 20 teams in both leagues.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/1968-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on September 29, which saw all teams play, except for the Baltimore Orioles and Cleveland Indians.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/1968-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 2 and October 10.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/1968-major-league-baseball-season] 6 tie games (3 in AL, 3 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/1968-major-league-baseball-season] The Detroit Tigers and New York Yankees had two tie games each.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/1968-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Indians and Oakland Athletics had one tie each.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/1968-major-league-baseball-season] The Atlanta Braves, Chicago Cubs, Cincinnati Reds, New York Mets, Pittsburgh Pirates, and San Francisco Giants had one tie each.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/1968-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 2 and ended on October 10 with the Detroit Tigers defeating the St.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/1968-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals in the 1968 World Series in seven games.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/1968-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/1968-major-league-baseball-season] With the relocation of the Kansas City Athletics from Kansas City, Missouri to Oakland, California as the Oakland Athletics, they leave Municipal Stadium (where they played 13 seasons) and move into Oakland–Alameda County Coliseum.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/1968-major-league-baseball-season] They would go on to play there for 57 seasons through 2024, before again relocating.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/1968-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Sox began playing select games in the former home of the Milwaukee Braves in Milwaukee, Wisconsin, at Milwaukee County Stadium, hosting nine of 81 home games, on May 15, 28, June 17, 24, July 11, 22, August 2, 8, and 26.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/1968-major-league-baseball-season] Though only 11% of home games, these nine games accounted for 33% of all home games attendance for the White Sox.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/1968-major-league-baseball-season] NBC was the exclusive national TV broadcaster of MLB, airing the weekend *Game of the Week*, the All-Star Game, and the World Series.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] The **2010 Seattle Mariners season** was the 34th season in franchise history.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] The Mariners finished the season with 61 wins and 101 losses.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] As the Texas Rangers won their first pennant that season, the Mariners became one of only two teams to have never played in the World Series, along with the Washington Nationals.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] The Nationals, however, eventually made it to, and won, the World Series 9 years later, leaving the Mariners as the sole franchise to have not played in the Fall Classic.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] Most of the 2009 major league coaching staff was retained, with the exception of third base coach Bruce Hines.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] Mike Brumley was named the new third base coach on October 30, 2009.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] On December 7, the Mariners announced their minor league staff.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] On October 19, 2009, catcher Kenji Johjima, the first Japanese-born catcher in Major League Baseball, exercised an opt-out clause in his contract and returned to playing in Nippon Professional Baseball.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] The Mariners also lost their home run leader, Russell Branyan, who declined a one-year deal with the Mariners to test the free agent market.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] Two-time Gold Glove winner Adrián Beltré opted for free agency on November 5, 2009, and later signed with the Boston Red Sox.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] The third baseman declined $12 million in arbitration from the Mariners only days after the team signed Chone Figgins *(see below)*.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] Beltre officially parted ways with the Mariners when he signed a one-year, $9 million deal with the Boston Red Sox.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] Pitcher Phillippe Aumont, noted as one of the top prospects in the organization, was sent to the Phillies in the trade for Cliff Lee.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] Also, pitcher Brandon Morrow was traded to the Toronto Blue Jays as well.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] Carlos Silva, whose time in Seattle was plagued by injury, was traded to the Chicago Cubs on December 18.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] Chone Figgins signed a four-year contract valued at $36 million.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] General manager Jack Zduriencik noted Figgins' versatility on defense and could ask him to play second base as well.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] Ken Griffey Jr. returned to the Mariners with a one-year deal after a successful 2009 season and large number of Seattle fans asking for "one more year." Shortstop Jack Wilson signed a two-year, $10 million deal to remain in Seattle.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] Wilson was one of the players received from the Pittsburgh Pirates at the trading deadline in 2009.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] On December 14, 2009, the Mariners, along with the three other organizations including the Philadelphia Phillies, the Toronto Blue Jays, and the Oakland Athletics agreed to a 4-team, 9-player deal.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] The Mariners received former Cy Young Award winner Cliff Lee from Philadelphia in exchange for three prospects as a complement to ace Félix Hernández.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] On December 18, 2009, the Mariners traded pitcher Carlos Silva and cash considerations to the Chicago Cubs for outfielder Milton Bradley, particularly noting his offensive capabilities.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] On December 22, the Mariners traded Brandon Morrow to the Toronto Blue Jays for pitcher Brandon League, and a minor league prospect.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] The Mariners acquired first baseman Casey Kotchman from the Boston Red Sox in exchange for utility player Bill Hall, a player to be named later, and cash considerations.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] On January 29, 2010, the Mariner signed outfielder Eric Byrnes to a one-year, $400,000 contract after he was released by the Arizona Diamondbacks.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] The Mariners signed first baseman Ryan Garko to a one-year $550,000 contract on February 1.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] On February 6, the Mariners re-signed pitcher Érik Bédard to a one-year, $1.5 million contract, with a mutual option for 2011.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] After the World Series, the Mariners cleared five spots from their 40-man roster after infielder Bryan LaHair, pitchers César Jiménez, Randy Messenger and Marwin Vega were outrighted to the Triple-A Tacoma Rainiers, and pitcher Justin Thomas was claimed off waivers by the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] The Mariners added seven new scouts after the season including the West Coast Supervisor Butch Baccala, Southern California scout John Ramey, Northwest scout Joe Ross, Midwest scout Tony Russo, Southwest scout Jess Kapellusch, Atlantic scout Mike Moriarty, and Gulf Coast scout Devitt Moore.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] On November 25, the Mariners re-signed minor league pitchers Steve Bray and Steven Shell, and catcher José Yépez.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] On December 9, the Mariners signed outfielder Corey Patterson to a minor league contract with an invitation to spring training.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] It was reported by *Baseball America* that the Mariners signed pitcher Levale Speigner and infielder Travis Denker, and also re-signed pitcher Chris Seddon and Josh Wilson to minor league contracts on December 12.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] On December 16, the Mariners signed 19-year-old Brazilian prospect Pedro Okuda to a minor league contract.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] During the trade for Cliff Lee, the Mariners gave up three prospects including pitchers Phillippe Aumont and J.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] On December 22, *Baseball America* reported that the Mariners re-signed pitcher Mike Koplove, and signed pitcher David Pauley, and catcher Ralph Henriquez Jr.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] During the trade for Brandon League, the Mariners also acquired minor league outfielder Johermyn Chávez from the Blue Jays.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] On December 28, the Mariners signed catcher Josh Bard, and re-signed pitcher Chad Cordero to minor league contracts with invitations to spring training.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] The Mariners signed free agent utility player Chris Woodward, who was in their organization during the first half of the 2009 season, to a minor league contract with an invitation to spring training.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] On January 13, the Mariners re-signed first baseman Brad Nelson to a minor league contract with and invitation to spring training.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] Formerly of the Milwaukee Brewers organization, Jesús Colomé signed a minor league contract with an invitation to spring training with the Mariners on February 10.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] On February 12, 2010, the Mariners signed Mike Sweeney, a player who MLB.com called a "key clubhouse component from the Mariners' dramatic 2009 turnaround", to a minor league contract with an invitation to spring training.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] During the offseason, MLB.com ranked Mariners' first round draft Dustin Ackley as the 15th best prospect in Minor League Baseball.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] *Baseball America* also ranked players by their specific talents.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] Five Mariners' players filed for salary arbitration in January 2010.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] The list of filers included pitchers David Aardsma, Félix Hernández, Brandon League and Mark Lowe, and first baseman Casey Kotchman.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] On January 18, Aardsma, Hernández and Lowe signed new contracts with the Mariners, avoiding arbitration.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] Aardsma signed a deal for $2.75 million, and Lowe signed a deal worth $1.15 million.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] Hernández's five-year deal was worth $80 million.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] On January 20, the Mariners came to an agreement with League for a one-year $900,000 deal, avoiding arbitration.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] Kotchman, the last arbitration eligible player on the Mariners roster, agreed to a $3.5 million contract on February 3, avoiding arbitration, and settling all the Mariners' arbitration cases.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] On February 8, newly acquired pitcher Cliff Lee underwent minor surgery to remove a floating bone spur in his left foot.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] Lee was expected to be out two-to-three weeks, making him unable to report to spring training at the scheduled time.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] On March 4, closer David Aardsma experienced tightness in his groin causing him to miss playing time.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] Shortstop Jack Wilson suffered from right hamstring tightness after a Mariners' game in early March.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] On March 19, it was announced that pitcher Cliff Lee could start the season on the disabled list because of a right lower abdominal strain.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] At the end of spring training, Lee was placed on the 15-day disabled list for the aforementioned reason.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] On April 3, Mariners' minor leaguer James McOwen dislocated his shoulder while attempting to catch a ball hit by Clint Barmes.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] On March 10, 2010, the Mariners cut 10 people from their spring roster including Ryan Feierabend, Josh Fields, Steven Shell, Nick Hill, Chris Seddon, Mauricio Robles, Luis Oliveros and Steven Baron.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] On March 17, the Mariners released pitcher Yusmeiro Petit whom they had claimed off waivers on November 4, 2009.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] Michael Saunders, an outfielder who played limited time with the Mariners in 2009, was optioned to the Triple-A Tacoma Rainiers on March 18.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] On March 18, the Mariners traded minor league pitcher Miguel Celestino to the Boston Red Sox to complete the trade for Casey Kotchman.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] First baseman Mike Carp was assigned to minor league camp on March 25, and was informed that he would start the season with the Triple-A Tacoma Rainiers.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] On March 31, outfielder Corey Patterson opted out of his contract with the Mariners and field for free agency.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] Also on March 31, the Mariners assigned pitcher Chad Cordero to minor league camp, and optioned Luke French to the Triple-A Tacoma Rainiers.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] Retired pitcher Randy Johnson agreed to throw out the ceremonial first pitch before the home opener at Safeco Field.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] Johnson, who spent 10 seasons in Seattle, reportedly accepted the request immediately.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] In the first game of the seasons against the Oakland Athletics at Oakland–Alameda County Coliseum, the Mariners won by a score of 5–3.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] Seattle reliever Brandon League got the win while Oakland reliever Brad Ziegler got the loss.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] On August 9 manager Don Wakamatsu was dismissed as manager and Daren Brown was named his replacement on an interim basis.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] The Mariners ended the season scoring only 513 runs, the lowest since the American League (AL) instituted the designated hitter in 1973.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2010-seattle-mariners-season] The Mariners were also last in the AL in team batting average at .236 and also ranked last in most other offensive categories this season.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The **2021 Major League Baseball All-Star Game** was the 91st Major League Baseball All-Star Game.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game was hosted by the Colorado Rockies and played at Coors Field on July 13.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] It was broadcast nationally by Fox, Fox Deportes, and ESPN Radio.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The American League (AL) defeated the National League (NL) 5–2.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] It was the eighth consecutive All-Star Game victory for the AL.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game was originally to be hosted in Atlanta at Truist Park.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] However, following the Georgia State Legislature's passage of the Election Integrity Act of 2021, the game was moved to Coors Field in Denver.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The All-Star Game was the second to be played in Denver after the 1998 game.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Kevin Cash of the Tampa Bay Rays managed the AL and Dave Roberts of the defending World Series champion Los Angeles Dodgers managed the NL.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] For the first time in All-Star Game history, Los Angeles Angels player Shohei Ohtani served as the starting pitcher and lead-off batter.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The matchup also featured the 200th home run of the All-Star Game, which was hit by Toronto Blue Jays player Vladimir Guerrero Jr.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Atlanta was originally awarded the game on May 30, 2019; it was to be the first All-Star Game hosted by Truist Park and the third All-Star Game played in Atlanta after the 1972 and 2000 editions.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] In March 2021, there were calls for the All-Star Game to be moved from Atlanta, in protest of the Georgia State Legislature's passage of the Election Integrity Act of 2021.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] A sizeable portion of the player base and fan base are Hispanic and that had factored into the relocation threat.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] In an interview with ESPN's Sage Steele on March 31, President Joe Biden stated that he would "strongly support" moving the game out of Georgia, saying that Republican efforts to make voting laws more restrictive following the 2020 presidential election were "Jim Crow on steroids".
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] On April 1, Manfred stated that he was "talking to various constituencies within the game and I'm just not going beyond that in terms of what I would consider or not consider." In an April 1 interview with Fox News, Georgia Governor Brian Kemp criticized the efforts, calling them "ridiculous".
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] On April 2, MLB announced that the game and the 2021 MLB draft (which was added to the All-Star festivities this year) would be moved from Georgia, and that the game would be relocated to a different city in another state, to be determined.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] In a statement shared on Truth Social, former President Donald Trump also criticized the decision, calling for a boycott of MLB.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Texas Governor Greg Abbott cancelled a planned appearance at the Texas Rangers' home opener, where he had been scheduled to throw out the first pitch, in protest of the decision to move the game.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] In a letter to the Rangers stating his decision, Abbott also wrote that he would not participate in any future events organized by MLB and that Texas would not bid to host future All-Star games or other MLB special events.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] (They would eventually host the All-Star game in 2024).
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] In a tweet, former President Barack Obama also praised MLB for moving the game out of Georgia.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Atlanta Mayor Keisha Lance Bottoms also supported the move.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] However, Bottoms, like Georgia's two United States Senators, represent Fulton County, while the Braves, and Truist Park, is located in Cobb County.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Legislators that represent Cobb County, home county of the Braves and Truist Park supported the bill.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] On April 14, five Republican senators and representatives introduced legislation to strip Major League Baseball of its antitrust exemption in response to the move.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] An April 5 Morning Consult poll found that 39% of U.S. adults approved of the move while 28% percent of U.S. adults disapproved, and 32% of U.S. adults stated they had no opinion or didn't know about the move.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Overall support for the move was higher among MLB fans, Democrats, and people of color compared to the general population.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Data from Morning Consult Brand Intelligence also showed that Republican approval of MLB dropped by 35 percentage points from 47 points to 12 points.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The 2021 MLB All-Star Game became at least the third major sporting event in the United States to be relocated for political reasons.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] On April 5, MLB announced that Coors Field in Denver would host the All-Star Game.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] On April 23, the All-Star Game logo was unveiled, featuring the Rockies' colors of purple, white, black, and silver with a profile representing the Rocky Mountains at the bottom.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] On June 24, MLB announced that players would wear standardized jerseys during the All-Star Game, rather than their own team's jerseys—navy blue for American League players and white for National League players.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Voting for each phase was independent; that is, votes did not carry over between phases.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] First phase voting was held from June 3 through June 24, and second phase voting was June 28 through July 1.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] All voting was conducted online, at MLB.com (or associated mobile applications) or via Google Search.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Starting players, as selected via voting, were announced on July 1.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Reserve position players and all pitchers—selected through "a combination of Player Ballot selections and choices made by the Commissioner’s Office"—were announced on July 4.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Under MLB rules, at least one player from each major-league team has to be selected for the game.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] However, there is no requirement for each team to have a player rostered for the game—for various reasons, each of the four players from the Houston Astros selected to the game became unavailable, leaving the Astros without a player on the American League's active roster for the game.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The total of 40 players named All-Stars for the first time set a new MLB record.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] **^** Freddy Peralta was named as the roster replacement for Brandon Woodruff due to Woodruff starting on Sunday.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] **^** Tim Anderson was named as the roster replacement for Carlos Correa due to Correa opting not to play.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] **^** Chris Bassitt was named as the roster replacement for Ryan Pressly due to Pressly opting not to play.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] **^** Whit Merrifield was named as the roster replacement for Jose Altuve due to injury.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] **^** Joey Wendle was named as the roster replacement for Michael Brantley due to injury.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] **^** Walker Buehler was named as the roster replacement for Yu Darvish due to injury.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] **^** Justin Turner was named as the roster replacement for Mookie Betts due to injury.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] **^** Max Scherzer was named as the roster replacement for Kevin Gausman due to Gausman starting on Sunday.
[src:win-loss-record-pitching/2021-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] **^** Yadier Molina was named as the roster replacement for Buster Posey due to injury.
